ype", "prob": 0.4805831015110016, "span": {"begin": 518, "end": 521}}, {"id": ["mesh:D013481"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "superoxide", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9995736479759216, "span": {"begin": 570, "end": 580}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "mammalian cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8835610151290894, "span": {"begin": 598, "end": 613}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7385"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "complex II", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.932964563369751, "span": {"begin": 615, "end": 625}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7385"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "mammalian complex II", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9901087284088135, "span": {"begin": 677, "end": 697}}, {"id": ["mesh:D013481"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "superoxide", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.999727189540863, "span": {"begin": 855, "end": 865}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7385"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "complex II", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.940579354763031, "span": {"begin": 934, "end": 944}}, {"id": ["mesh:D013481"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "superoxide", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.999721348285675, "span": {"begin": 1015, "end": 1025}}, {"id": ["mesh:D019802"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "succinate", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9987188577651978, "span": {"begin": 1088, "end": 1097}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "complex", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.4956595003604889, "span": {"begin": 1299, "end": 1306}}, {"id": ["mesh:D019802"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "succinate", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9941046833992004, "span": {"begin": 1360, "end": 1369}}, {"id": ["mesh:D013481"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "superoxide", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9945932030677795, "span": {"begin": 1432, "end": 1442}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7385"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "complex II", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9787470698356628, "span": {"begin": 1503, "end": 1513}}], "text": "Succinate dehydrogenase (SDH) is a 4 subunit mitochondrial enzyme that oxidises succinate to fumarate, with the corresponding reduction of FAD to FADH2. FADH2 is subsequently reoxidised by transfer of electrons to the mitochondrial electron transfer chain (ETC). SDH thus links the tricarboxylic acid (TCA) cycle to mitochondrial electron transfer. It is the only TCA cycle enzyme to be embedded in the mitochondrial inner membrane, as opposed to located free in the mitochondrial matrix, comprising complex II of the ETC. The mitochondrial ETC is the largest source of superoxide radicals in most mammalian cells, complex II being one source of those radicals.  Inhibition of mammalian complex II activity has been recorded for many chemicals, including fungicides, other environmental chemicals and pharmaceuticals, being associated with an increase in superoxide generation in some instances. Because of the size and complexity of complex II, with multipled potential binding sites for inhibitors, generation of superoxide radical is not, per se, a guaranteed outcome of inhibition of succinate oxidation. The site and nature of the enzyme-inhibitor interaction is potential determining factor.  This KER is concerned with the direct reversible or irreversible binding of inhibitory chemicals to complex II, leading to a reduction in the dehydrogenation of succinate, and the potential for consequent generation of mitochondrial superoxide radicals. Other effects, such as reduction in expression of complex II components, are not covered.  &nbsp;", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 15:48:23 +0000 2026"}